The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Saturday, August 07, 2004 				 India Inc dials Taiwan number
 ALOKANANDA GHOSH																								Calcutta, Aug. 6: A Confederation of Indian Industry (CII) delegation on telecom and broadband will visit Taiwan as part of its Invest India mission from September 14 to 17 to identify areas of mutual co-operation and technology transfer between the two countries.																								A CII spokesperson said, The delegation will meet specialised telecom companies to pursue business opportunities in technology and products. It will also study the possibility of rural telephony and explore opportunities in telecom software.																								Taiwan is a major telecom and broadband equipment hub in Asia. Its products include cellphones, switches, protocol security and network management. The country also has a strong design and research and development base.																								The visit is significant as India is trying to replicate the success of the Chinese cellular products manufacturing industry, which currently controls more than 25 per cent of the global production.																								Manufacturing Committee chairman Pankaj Mohindroo, who had visited China last month to study the handset makers, will accompany the delegation.																								The committee, which is actively promoting a strong handset manufacturing base in the country, met Union IT minister Dayanidhi Maran today to highlight the advantages of an indigenous industry.																								The committee has also appointed KPMG Advisory Services to prepare a position paper that will help identify growth areas for the industry and make India globally competitive in handset, component and accessories manufacturing. Initially, the country has set a production target of $5 billion. The handset industry is estimated at Rs 8000 crore. 
